author: @amishkhatu5186
text: I also tried multiple solutions to solve the CSS problem as the static_files were not getting effective . Even the solutions in the comments didn't work for me. What actually worked:- moving the static folder to the main app folder i.e blog (where views file exists) -> changes in the settings,py as : STATIC_ROOT =  "os.path.join(BASE_DIR, 'static')" STATICFILES_DIRS = [     os.path.join(BASE_DIR, 'myapp/static'), ]  and then running command as>> python manage.py collectstatic atlast >> python manage.py runserver done!!

author: @adog_6484
text: Hey guys i know some of you are having issues with your main.css loading at around 38:00. There are two things to look out for here. 1. Make sure you typed your link tag correctly: <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="{% static 'blog/main.css' %}"> 2. Make sure you are in debug mode: in settings.py, DEBUG = True, and ALLOWED_HOSTS = [].     If you are deploying it with DEBUG = False, then you should read this documentation on deploying static files: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.2/howto/static-files/deployment/

text:
Hi Corey, Thank you very much for this tutorial. I am following along and learning a lot! I have a question please. After reading about the HTML "main tag" at https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/main#Usage_notes "The content of a
element should be unique to the document. Content that is repeated across a set of documents or document sections such as sidebars, navigation links, copyright information, site logos, and search forms shouldn't be included unless the search form is the main function of the page." Since the side bar is most likely not unique to a specific HTML template, I was wondering why you decided to have it inside HTML main tag then? author: @DanielRodrigues-nd4lu
text: For those who are seeing errors  following the last part of the video (around 42:00),  the base template  part href  = "{%  url  < insert some url here >  %}" , it is probably because of the Django version used in the video being outdated. Newer Django versions require  the addition of a namespace to the paths in the urls.py files (both project and app ones).   You can do this by going into the  project/urls.py  file and adding a "namespace" field inside the include function, for instance           path( ' ' , include( ' blog.urls ' , namespace = " < insert you namespace here >" ) )  Then, inside the base HTML file, on the  "href", you should basically add inside of the quotes the prefix  ' < the namespace > : ' before the url. More precisely:           href = {% url  ' < insert the namespace of the url that you want to use here > :  < insert the url here >  '   %}  On the blog/urls.py you can simply add a variable with a string after imports, for instance           blog_namespace = " < insert the desired name here > "  Hope that it helps.

I wanted to add that when I'm using Django 3.0.5 in combination with Pycharm 2019.3.4 I noticed the following:   When I'm creating the /static/MyApp/main.css and trying to reference everything to that Directory it trows the    "GET /static/myApp/main.css HTTP/1.1" 404 1674    It seems that in the settings.py the following code needs to be added to the bottom:   STATICFILES_DIRS = [     os.path.join(BASE_DIR, 'static'), ]   and then it's working fine. Could be a version issue with Django, I hope it helps.

author: @eugene5976
text: I have created this function to support activate the profile for Python Virtual Environment. Hope this help. # This is support Python ENV # But strictly naming with venv_<Project_Name> # Append these into ${HOME}/.zprofile, .bash_profile, or .profile. Depend on your current shell. activate() { CURR_DIR=${PWD##*/} PROJECT_NAME=${CURR_DIR} VENV_DIR=venv_${PROJECT_NAME} if [ -d ${VENV_DIR} ]; then  source ${VENV_DIR}/bin/activate  echo "Load \"${PROJECT_NAME}\" Python Virtual Environment." else  echo "Please go to base directory of project."  echo "Typically created venv_<Project_Name> to support \"activate\" function." fi }

author: @Navyblue0785
text: If youre having issues with the CSS file not loading or the navigation bar overlapping, I found the solution, after at least 2 weeks, and it's very simple: the reason your css file is not loading is because you have it placed in the wrong directory. the confusion comes with having 2 blog directory. so this is how it should be: Blog/static/blog/main.css. Mine was under Blog/blog/static/main.css which is wrong. Hope this helps!    source: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/howto/static-files/
